                      <bibl><ptr target="#AnagnostopoulouGalaniMenti2022"/>, <citedRange>243 n. 15</citedRange> (on oracular questions about professional activity)</bibl>.
                    </p>
                          </div>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc">
                    <ab>
                        <lb n="1"/>προβατεύ  μ; 
                        </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                <p>Shall I work as a shepherd or not?</p>
            </div>
                <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="es">
              <p>¿Me dedico al pastoreo o no?</p>
                    </div>
                <div type="commentary" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en"> 
                    <p>For questions concerning animal husbandry (a frequent topic of enquiry in the Dodona oracular corpus), see the commentaries of the first editors and <bibl><ptr target="#AnagnostopoulouGalaniMenti2022"/>, <citedRange>243</citedRange>. </bibl></p>
                    
   <p n="Ithaca Results">Ithaca identifies Epirus as the most probable geographical origin of the inscription (40.77%), followed by the Saronic Gulf, Corinthia, and the Argolid (33.12%). Chronologically, the highest probability is assigned to the interval 550-540 BC (9.49%), although the interval 450-440 BC receives a nearly identical probability (8.80%).
   See <ref target="https://dodonaonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/IDodoneOnline8B_2026_06_29.html">Ithaca results</ref> and <ref target="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/IDodone/IDodoneOnline/refs/heads/main/ithaca-results/IDodoneOnline8B.md">metadata</ref>, and a snapshot of the <ref target="https://dodonaonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/IDodoneOnline8B_geographical-attribution_2026_06.jpg">geographical attribution</ref>.</p>
            </div>
